<section xml:id="lesson-01-review">
  <title>Lesson 1 – Functions and Their Graphs</title>

  <exercise xml:id="l1-ex1">
      <statement>
        <p>Determine whether the following relations represent functions. If it is not a function, explain why not.</p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li><m>\{(1,2),(-3,3),(6,3)\}</m></li>
          <li><m>\{(-4,4),(8,2),(-4,7)\}</m></li>
          <li><m>\{(1,-9),(-8,3),(-5,7)\}</m></li>
          <li><m>xy - x = 5</m></li>
          <li><m>2x + y^4 = 3</m></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Solution explanation.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="l1-ex2">
      <statement>
        <p>Evaluate each function for the given values. If the function is undefined, write <em>undefined</em>.</p>
          <p>For each function, evaluate <m>f(3)</m>, <m>f(x-3)</m>, and <m>f(-x)</m>.</p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li><m>f(x)=x^3-x^2+1</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x)=2\sqrt{x+7}+1</m></li>
          <li><m>f(x)=\frac{x+4}{x^2-9}</m></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Work and simplification.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="l1-ex3">
      <statement>
        <p>Identify which of the following graphs are functions. Explain why or why not.</p>

